ved human dominance. Written in engaging, accessible prose, Amazonia in the Anthropocene offers an innovative contribution to debates about humanity’s place on the planet, encouraging deeper ecocentric thinking and a more inclusive vision of ecology for the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aClimatic changeszAmazon River Region. 0aHuman beingsxEffect of environment onzAmazon River Region. 0aHuman ecologyzAmazon River Region. 0aHuman geographyzAmazon River Region. 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/30799140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477308004423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477308004/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK